 ('16', '25', '9', '1', 'en_us', NULL, '{\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"Interaction Design Assignment Submission\",\"slug\":\"interaction-design-assignment-submission\",\"postDate\":1381662884,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"fields\":{\"2\":\"<p>Set<\\/p>\",\"1\":\"Hello\",\"6\":[\"7\"],\"3\":\"\",\"10\":\"\"}}', '2013-10-13 11:14:44', '2013-10-13 11:14:44', '0e8e5860-69d2-45a4-9262-cdd5b52bc7c1'),
 ('17', '26', '10', '1', 'en_us', NULL, '{\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"Assignment 1\",\"slug\":\"assignment-1\",\"postDate\":1381663861,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"fields\":{\"2\":\"<p>Each group member to evaluate the mockups from Task 1c using one of the following methods:<\\/p><ul>\\r\\n<li>Usability test (with at least 2 users)<\\/li><li>Heuristic analysis (with at least 2 experts) using the <a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.useit.com\\/papers\\/heuristic\\/heuristic_list.html\\\">10 usability heuristics<\\/a> or the <a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/designingwebinterfaces.com\\/6-tips-for-a-great-flex-ux-part-5\\\">web application heuristics<\\/a>.<\\/li><li>Controlled experiment (with at least 2 users)<\\/li><\\/ul><p>To evaluate the mockups, you need to:<\\/p><ul>\\r\\n<li>Print your mockups<\\/li><li>Prepare your mockups for the evaluation if necessary, such as interactive elements like radio buttons, pop-up boxes, etc.<\\/li><li>Prepare any additional material needed for the study, such as task lists<\\/li><li>Recruit participants (NB: People from your class qualify as experts, but not as users<\\/li><\\/ul><p>Additionally you should conduct a short post-evaluation interview with your users or experts to find out about their general attitude towards your application concept, what things they liked about, what they didn\\u2019t, whether they were missing any features, etc.<\\/p><p>The minimum requirement is to evaluate the desktop version of your application, but you might want to include the mobile version as well to get early feedback from users\\/experts on this part as well.<\\/p><p><strong>Submission<\\/strong><br>Individual or group blog post describing, including the following:<\\/p><ul>\\r\\n<li>Short description of method<\\/li><li>Description of evaluation procedure, including the number of people tested and what their demographics are, such as age, profession, etc.<\\/li><li>One or more photos of your evaluation session. To respect the privacy of your participants take the photos from an angle in which their face isn\\u2019t visible.<\\/li><li>Findings: what were the main results of the evaluation as well as the post-evaluation interview<\\/li><li>Suggestions for improvements to the interface based on the findings<\\/li><\\/ul><p>The blog post submission is due on <del>Thursday 13 September<\\/del> Sunday 16 September, 8pm. (There is no Blackboard submission.)<\\/p><p>The next task \\u2014 to develop the interactive prototype \\u2014 is due 11 October.<\\/p><p><strong>Resources<\\/strong><br><a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/web.arch.usyd.edu.au\\/~mtomitsch\\/teaching\\/2012\\/deco2200\\/material\\/Designbrief.pdf\\\">Design brief<\\/a> (pdf)<br><a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.useit.com\\/papers\\/heuristic\\/heuristic_evaluation.html\\\">How to conduct a heuristic evaluation<\\/a><br><a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/designingwebinterfaces.com\\/6-tips-for-a-great-flex-ux-part-5\\\">10 heuristics in web applications<\\/a><br><a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.useit.com\\/papers\\/heuristic\\/heuristic_list.html\\\">Nielsen\\u2019s 10 usability heuristics<\\/a><br><a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.useit.com\\/alertbox\\/20000319.html\\\">Why you only need to test with 5 users<\\/a><br><a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/dschool.stanford.edu\\/wp-content\\/uploads\\/2011\\/03\\/BootcampBootleg2010v2SLIM.pdf\\\">d.school bootcamp bootleg\\u2028<\\/a> (pdf) \\u2014 see pages 34 and 35<br><a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.ok-cancel.com\\/\\\">OK\\/Cancel<\\/a> \\u2014 comics on usability and human computer interaction<\\/p><p><a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.userfocus.co.uk\\/articles\\/index.html\\\" style=\\\"font-family: Arial, Helvetica, Verdana, Tahoma, sans-serif;\\\">User Focus<\\/a> \\u2014 articles and resources\\u2028 for further reading<\\/p>\",\"11\":\"\",\"3\":[\"new:Heuristic Evaluation\",\"new:Usability\",\"new:User Focus\"],\"10\":\"\"}}', '2013-10-13 11:31:01', '2013-10-13 11:31:01', '704f6a9b-107f-4dfd-9e81-d3ba99384ce0'),
 ('18', '4', '3', '1', 'en_us', NULL, '{\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"Design Lab Featured Content\",\"slug\":\"design-lab-featured-content\",\"postDate\":1381641240,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"fields\":{\"2\":\"\",\"12\":[\"10\"],\"10\":\"\"}}', '2013-10-13 11:55:15', '2013-10-13 11:55:15', 'b1679821-998d-4811-871f-c1253622f2fa'),
 ('19', '4', '3', '1', 'en_us', NULL, '{\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"Design Lab Featured Content\",\"slug\":\"design-lab-featured-content\",\"postDate\":1381641240,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"fields\":{\"2\":\"\",\"4\":[\"17\",\"20\"],\"10\":\"\"}}', '2013-10-13 12:05:45', '2013-10-13 12:05:45', 'bee2ac4e-8447-4212-b290-52c0a604ae91'),
 ('20', '17', '10', '1', 'en_us', NULL, '{\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"Interaction Design Item\",\"slug\":\"interaction-design-item\",\"postDate\":1381650600,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"fields\":{\"2\":\"<p>Some people have run into an issue with their BB10 app looking oversized when they tested on the actual device. This is because the BB10 has a high pixel density ratio and web content seems to be rendered by default at a low dpi. The effect is that all of the elements in your app look enlarged. <em>Note that this only happens when you explicitly set the width and height css elements on the &lt;body&gt; to 768px and 1280px respectively.<\\/em><\\/p><p>For most people who have not set the width and height of their &lt;body&gt; or any elements it contains to a certain pixel value and have instead set them to either 100% or just let the elements fill the space, this enlargement issue won\\u2019t happen. What will happen is that your app will render at about 160 pixels per inch. The BB10 however is capable of a resolution of <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/developer.blackberry.com\\/devzone\\/design\\/devices_and_screen_sizes.html\\\">356 ppi<\\/a>. That means you are missing out on utilising the full resolution of the device and making a really great looking app.<\\/p><p>The solution is to adjust the \\u201cviewport\\u201d meta tag slightly. Usually we have had an attribute called \\u201cinitial-scale\\u201d that we set to 1.0 meaning that the app is neither zoomed in or out. To adjust for the higher pixel density in the BB10 we want to zoom out slightly. This means setting the \\u201cinitial-scale\\u201d to about 0.446.<\\/p><p>So your \\u201cviewport\\u201d meta tag should now look like this:<\\/p><p>&lt;meta name=\\u201dviewport\\u201d content=\\u201dwidth=device-width,initial-scale=0.446,user-scalable=no\\u201d&gt;<\\/p><p>You may have to adjust your html elements to suit the new resolution of your app. However it will be worth the effort when you end up with a much better looking app.<\\/p><p><strong>Reference:<\\/strong> <a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/supportforums.blackberry.com\\/t5\\/Web-and-WebWorks-Development\\/How-to-set-up-the-viewport-for-a-BlackBerry-WebWorks-application\\/ta-p\\/1943807\\\">How to set up the viewport for a BlackBerry WebWorks application for BlackBerry 10<\\/a><\\/p>\",\"5\":\"Design Computing\",\"7\":[\"22\"],\"3\":[\"18\"],\"8\":[\"Interaction Design\"],\"10\":\"\"}}', '2013-10-13 13:28:04', '2013-10-13 13:28:04', '6ee713c4-d8d2-4a4a-91b8-ea69ab79c01c'),
 ('21', '17', '10', '1', 'en_us', NULL, '{\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"Making your BB10 app high resolution\",\"slug\":\"interaction-design-item\",\"postDate\":1381650600,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"fields\":{\"2\":\"<p>Some people have run into an issue with their BB10 app looking oversized when they tested on the actual device. This is because the BB10 has a high pixel density ratio and web content seems to be rendered by default at a low dpi. The effect is that all of the elements in your app look enlarged. <em>Note that this only happens when you explicitly set the width and height css elements on the &lt;body&gt; to 768px and 1280px respectively.<\\/em><\\/p><p>For most people who have not set the width and height of their &lt;body&gt; or any elements it contains to a certain pixel value and have instead set them to either 100% or just let the elements fill the space, this enlargement issue won\\u2019t happen. What will happen is that your app will render at about 160 pixels per inch. The BB10 however is capable of a resolution of <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/developer.blackberry.com\\/devzone\\/design\\/devices_and_screen_sizes.html\\\">356 ppi<\\/a>. That means you are missing out on utilising the full resolution of the device and making a really great looking app.<\\/p><p>The solution is to adjust the \\u201cviewport\\u201d meta tag slightly. Usually we have had an attribute called \\u201cinitial-scale\\u201d that we set to 1.0 meaning that the app is neither zoomed in or out. To adjust for the higher pixel density in the BB10 we want to zoom out slightly. This means setting the \\u201cinitial-scale\\u201d to about 0.446.<\\/p><p>So your \\u201cviewport\\u201d meta tag should now look like this:<\\/p><p>&lt;meta name=\\u201dviewport\\u201d content=\\u201dwidth=device-width,initial-scale=0.446,user-scalable=no\\u201d&gt;<\\/p><p>You may have to adjust your html elements to suit the new resolution of your app. However it will be worth the effort when you end up with a much better looking app.<\\/p><p><strong>Reference:<\\/strong> <a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/supportforums.blackberry.com\\/t5\\/Web-and-WebWorks-Development\\/How-to-set-up-the-viewport-for-a-BlackBerry-WebWorks-application\\/ta-p\\/1943807\\\">How to set up the viewport for a BlackBerry WebWorks application for BlackBerry 10<\\/a><\\/p>\",\"5\":\"Design Computing\",\"7\":[\"22\"],\"3\":[\"18\"],\"8\":[\"Interaction Design\"],\"10\":\"\"}}', '2013-10-13 13:28:27', '2013-10-13 13:28:27', '6fa3992c-366d-4ab2-9b3f-f584ed3d1749'),
 ('22', '17', '10', '1', 'en_us', NULL, '{\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"Making your BB10 app high resolution\",\"slug\":\"interaction-design-item\",\"postDate\":1381650600,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"fields\":{\"2\":\"<p>Some people have run into an issue with their BB10 app looking oversized when they tested on the actual device. This is because the BB10 has a high pixel density ratio and web content seems to be rendered by default at a low dpi. The effect is that all of the elements in your app look enlarged. <em>Note that this only happens when you explicitly set the width and height css elements on the &lt;body&gt; to 768px and 1280px respectively.<\\/em><\\/p><p>For most people who have not set the width and height of their &lt;body&gt; or any elements it contains to a certain pixel value and have instead set them to either 100% or just let the elements fill the space, this enlargement issue won\\u2019t happen. What will happen is that your app will render at about 160 pixels per inch. The BB10 however is capable of a resolution of <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/developer.blackberry.com\\/devzone\\/design\\/devices_and_screen_sizes.html\\\">356 ppi<\\/a>. That means you are missing out on utilising the full resolution of the device and making a really great looking app.<\\/p><p>The solution is to adjust the \\u201cviewport\\u201d meta tag slightly. Usually we have had an attribute called \\u201cinitial-scale\\u201d that we set to 1.0 meaning that the app is neither zoomed in or out. To adjust for the higher pixel density in the BB10 we want to zoom out slightly. This means setting the \\u201cinitial-scale\\u201d to about 0.446.<\\/p><p>So your \\u201cviewport\\u201d meta tag should now look like this:<\\/p><p>&lt;meta name=\\u201dviewport\\u201d content=\\u201dwidth=device-width,initial-scale=0.446,user-scalable=no\\u201d&gt;<\\/p><p>You may have to adjust your html elements to suit the new resolution of your app. However it will be worth the effort when you end up with a much better looking app.<\\/p><p><strong>Reference:<\\/strong> <a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/supportforums.blackberry.com\\/t5\\/Web-and-WebWorks-Development\\/How-to-set-up-the-viewport-for-a-BlackBerry-WebWorks-application\\/ta-p\\/1943807\\\">How to set up the viewport for a BlackBerry WebWorks application for BlackBerry 10<\\/a><\\/p>\",\"5\":\"Design Computing\",\"7\":[\"22\"],\"1\":\"Some people have run into an issue with their BB10 app looking oversized when they tested on the actual device. \",\"3\":[\"18\"],\"8\":[\"Interaction Design\"],\"10\":\"\"}}', '2013-10-13 13:39:58', '2013-10-13 13:39:58', 'a3d54fb9-4b77-4688-bd39-42e9b37e0501'),
 ('23', '32', '7', '1', 'en_us', NULL, '{\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"Little Boxes\",\"slug\":\"little-boxes\",\"postDate\":1381718563,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"fields\":{\"2\":\"\",\"5\":\"Design Computing\",\"13\":\"\",\"7\":[\"31\"],\"14\":\"<p>Our concept, while still developing is centred around the idea of creating a room in which the user can login to and revisit both their online lives in the present or reverse the room to a time in their past. The goal is to immerse the user in their present and past as seamlessly as possible, while exhibiting their digital lives in an ordinary room, we want to use as many online sources of personal information as we can get, but realise the most ubiquitous source is more than likely Facebook, as it has the largest user base. We want to achieve this with a combination of images, audio, personal information and video, taken directly from Facebook using a mobile to login, with content both from the users profile and content relevant to when the user is choosing to view.<\\/p>\",\"20\":\"\",\"15\":\"\",\"6\":[\"1\"],\"18\":\"\",\"19\":\"<p>Little Boxes is an interactive, digital time-capsule that allows viewers not only to become a part of the piece directly but also to explore digital information in an interesting way. Various wooden boxes of different sizes, shapes and designs are scattered around the space, each with their own screen stored inside. On entering the space, visitors are prompted to do two things; log into their Facebook account and choose a month and year they wish to view.<\\/p>\",\"16\":\"\",\"17\":\"\",\"3\":[\"new:Physical Computing\",\"new:Time Capsules\",\"new:Social Networks\"],\"8\":\"Interaction Design\",\"10\":\"\"}}', '2013-10-14 02:42:43', '2013-10-14 02:42:43', '0acb111c-144d-44bc-9b3d-b8437fb8a93d'),
